==English==
{{was wotd|2020|April|20}}
===Etymology===
{{PIE word|en|yóh₁r̥}}{{root|en|ine-pro|*dī-}}
[[File:US Navy 070426-N-4965F-003 Six memorial candles are lit during a Holocaust Remembrance Day ceremony at Sharkey Theater on board Naval Station Pearl Harbor.jpg|thumb|Yahrzeit candles lit for a {{w|Yom HaShoah}} or [[Holocaust]] [[remembrance|Remembrance]] [[day|Day]] [[ceremony]] at {{w|Naval Station Pearl Harbor}} in [[Hawaii]], USA, in April 2007.]]
Borrowed from {{bor|en|yi|יאָרצײַט}}, from {{der|en|gmh|jārzīt|t=anniversary; Christian commemoration of a person’s death}}; from {{der|en|gmh|jār|t=year}} (from {{der|en|goh|jār|t=year}}, ultimately from {{der|en|ine-pro|*yóh₁r̥|*yéh₁n-|year}}) + {{der|en|gmh|zīt|t=time}} (from {{der|en|goh|zīt|t=time}}, ultimately from {{der|en|ine-pro|*dī-|t=time}}).<ref>Compare {{R:OED Online|pos=n|id=231129|date=September 2018|nodot=yes}}; {{R:Lexico|pos=n}}</ref> The Yiddish word is cognate with {{cog|de|Jahreszeit|t=season}}, which heavily influenced the spelling and pronunciation once the word was borrowed into English. {{doublet|en|yeartide}}.
